        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> With [noice.nvim](https://github.com/folke/noice.nvim) I already get :messages in a buffer, but with less effort.\r\n\r\nThat is not \"less effort\", noice does _a lot_ of heavy lifting for this, which it shouldn't have to.\r\n\r\nAnd I'm not talking about _all_ messages in a buffer; I'm talking about not (ab)using `:messages` for long-form output in the first place.\r\n\r\n> Therefore it makes sense to me to allow the maximum value to be configured by the user.\r\n\r\nBut options are not free; adding this may be a small number of lines of code, but you also need to\r\n1. document it;\r\n2. ensure that even unreasonable values are handled gracefully (what if someone sets `msghistory=0`?);\r\n3. ensure that it interacts well with other options and plugins (remember `cmdheight=0`?).\r\n\r\nEspecially 3. implies that adding options adds a superlinear amount of work. So this needs to be worth it, and I am not (yet) convinced of this here. I'm also not convinced that it _is_ a \"matter of taste\".\r\n\r\nSo the first step here is to investigate whether just raising the current value to, say, `2000` has any performance implications.\r\n",
